segments.text: whether it makes it legal illegal what makes it right or wrong is whether you win or lose you know this country hasn't settled anything since world war ii and you can never and i say never and i mean never you can never settle any political confrontation by political means when that first bullet has been fired you cannot settle it politically
You have to go in there and finish it.
And whoever wins, they're the ones that's right.
They had the biggest dig.
They won.
We settled the Pacific Front with Japan.
It was settled.
Y'all lost, and we won.
We settled the European Front.
Germany, y'all lost, and we won.
There wasn't any negotiations.
It's not, we'll sign if you give us.
It was unconditional surrender.
It was settled.
It was finished.
It was over with.
Vietnam has been, I've been here 20 years, back 20 years.
It's still not settled.
It's not going to be settled.
It will never be settled, ever.
It will not be settled.
It cannot be settled politically.
It can only be settled by force.
When we're talking about the South Vietnamese Army, did you ever feel that they had a real desire to be fighting the North Vietnamese?
No.
I think they were just doing what they had.
They were kind of caught between a rock and a hard place, too.
You know, they didn't want to leave their families.
If you don't leave, you know, what do you got to do?
What do you got to fight?
So they just would go visit when they wanted, come back and fight when they wanted?
Yeah.
I mean, they suffered for it when they got back, you know.
I mean, they were beaten, thrown in prison, thrown in stockades, thrown in, I've seen lots of things happen to them, you know, personally.
It's just that, but if you didn't go home, I mean, when would you go home?
When you came back here from Vietnam, what was life like?
Was it hard for you to adjust back to these surroundings as a civilian?
Did you have flashbacks from over there?
No, I haven't ever had any flashbacks.
I don't know if it's because I was a little older when I went over there.
Most of those kids were 18, 19, 20 years old.
Well, crud, that's just a baby.
I had my 25th birthday sitting on top of my tank, you know, in effect.
So I was, you know,
mid-twenties.
And maybe those few extra years gave me a little bit more time emotionally to mature out or whatever.
But I've seen little red-headed freckle-faced kids hop off a chopper, you know, wouldn't hurt a fly, never hurt a fly.
He's there, you know, serve his country.
And, you know, it's still not real to him.
But the first firefight that you get into it, if you survive,
What happens is you basically turn into a real cold, hard animal.
And there again, that's hard to explain to somebody that hadn't done that.
And it's kind of like you have a hard time, even your World War II veterans and Korean veterans.
They don't really understand the Vietnam veteran mindset.
They don't understand why most of the Vietnam veterans don't join the VFW.
They don't join the American Legion.
And these World War II times have done a lot of outreaching to those people, and it's met with little success.
Why is it that they don't?
I don't know for sure, but I think part of it might be if you'll talk to a Vietnam, I mean a World War II veteran, he was with H Company of the Fourth Army or something like that.
And they went over there.
They trained as a unit.
They went over there as a unit.
They stayed there for the duration as a unit.
Everyone knew everyone.
If you'll look in the San Antonio paper, you'll see that the 318th Bomb Squadron is having its 40th reunion this year or something like that.
And all these different units have all these reunions.
They're still having reunions.
They have them all the time.
They meet in Hawaii.
They meet in Phoenix.
They meet in San Antonio.
They'll meet in Miami.
And they had this closeness that they were all there together.
Vietnam wasn't like that.
You didn't know anybody.
Because everybody was always coming and going.
You know, all these people that were in and out all the time.
I don't know anybody.
You know, and I certainly don't have anything in common with the World War II times, you know.
And even though I've shown my little movies and stuff like that for some VFW and some American Legion, I've shown those, you know.
But, you know.
There wasn't that.
There was not that closeness where you really got to know everybody and you did something for four years together.
Because you were being transferred, going and joining other... Yeah.
I mean, like for me, I was in four, you might say four different units, you know, with people coming and going all the time.
I can see that.
So you really, I mean, it's just a bunch of strangers, you know.
Yet you might come back to your hometown...
and you might know somebody who was there and you have a little comradeship there.
You had something in common with this person and that person.
But to answer your question, I don't have any flashbacks.
I think about it a lot.
When I came back, I came back to Lubbock, Texas, which was basically a very conservative, very patriotic area of the country.

you know, I got all this baby killer, why did you go over there, you know, you're the one that's wrong, you know, I didn't get any, you know, when Johnny come marching home again type, there was no parades, there was no, you know, anything like that.
I had one thing on a positive nature really that, and that happened in Kerrville, Texas in 1986 when I first came to Kerrville.
I had a girl
that I just happened to mention that I was in Vietnam.
And she just put her arm around me and hugged me and said, thank you.
I just met her.
That's the only person that's ever said, you might say, to me, anything positive.
And that was many, many years after?
Yeah.
But it's not that there are not a lot of people out there that don't feel that way.
you just had one person, you know.
And not that I'm looking for it, I just kind of think that, you know, probably had it not happened, I wouldn't think anything about it, but because it did, I do think something about it.
Um, your views, have they changed since the end of the war, and how do you view the war?
Do you view it the same way?
Yeah, I think I do.
I wouldn't mind going back to Vietnam.
But the only way I would go to Vietnam or any other Vietnam-like place, whether it's Nicaragua or someplace like that, the only basis I would go down there on would be that you leave me alone.
You want me to do a job, I'll do it.
But I ain't going to stop.
And you're not going to stop me.
Have an unconditional.
Have an unconditional.
If you want to go down there, hey, guys, we need your help, fine.
I'll be the first one on the ship.
But you're not going to tell me don't shoot in a banana plantation.
Don't shoot in a rubber plantation, because you're going to damage a plant.
I ain't going to play that kind of stuff again.
So tell me in general how the American soldiers felt about these situations.
Well, of course, I guess everybody has their own little personal observation on it.
Another thing that really, really irritated me about most of the Vietnam movies that I've seen, especially Platoon, it perpetrated to me the American soldier as a very negative type person.
I told you I've spoken at probably 200 different little organizations over the years, and I have found, and part of my little speech that I give is that
you can be proud of the way the American fighting man conducted himself out in the field.
Because what I observed was he did it on as gentlemanly a basis as you could expect.
And I personally was proud of the way the American conducted himself.
But yet you have the news media in Hollywood perpetrates an entirely different picture and how many people get to listen to Mike Sullivan?
Not very many.
That's because when these people on television know what sells money.
That's right.
And they have a personal axe to grind to, and I wish there was no wars in the world, and I wish there was no diseases out there, too.
But there is, and you can't just play ostrich and bury your head in the sand and play like it's not happening.
And I think we do that as a nation, you know,
These same people, though, I'm talking about your Kennedys, your Jane Fondas, those kind of people, who get up there and say, oh, let's don't get in a war.
And nobody likes war.
And especially, you know, the military don't like it because they're the guys out doing it.
So they really don't like it.
But yet I think most people really realize that America didn't just happen and there has been some blood spilt.

and that we today are deriving the benefits from that past sacrifice and people forget about that and these thinking politicians are selling those basic freedoms and rights away every day little by little they're sitting there and they're just duck nibbling you every day you lose a little bit more and because
Well, there's no sense in getting upset about it.
It's not that big of a deal.
This is like giving a nice example.
That, to me, is like two days ago, and I found that kid down in Mexico.
And I personally, it really bothered me.
I mean, I woke up at night, and it was 4 o'clock in the morning.
I couldn't go to sleep just thinking about that and disgusted here at the bank.
I got more upset about it.
But yet now, another day's gone by, and it's not as upsetting to me.
So, you know, we'll just forget about it.
No sense rounding up an army and going out there and buying the suckers.
So you forget about that.
You forget about lots of things like that.
Well, that really irritates me.
And I think another nice deal that's happening right now, it's happening right this very minute, is Exxon makes a mistake.
And the price of the gasoline pumps already got up 20 cents a gallon.
I heard this morning that President Texaco said it's going to go up at least another 25 cents a gallon.
And what?
The price of oil hadn't gone up.
And they're going to have a 50% increase in price and no price in crude going up?
The same old deal is the American taxpayers getting screwed.
The American working slobs out there paying for somebody else's mistakes.
Whether it's big corporations or big government, we're still going to pay for their mistakes.
See, they're not responsible for anything.
And that's a big problem in America is our government
technically makes nobody responsible for anything.
And those are your liberties that are getting eaten away with because you've got these crime figures that are out there taking things away from you and nothing happens to them.
You know what I'm talking about.
And even if you caught them, what would happen to them?
And what do you think is going to happen to them if they catch the sucker?
You think they'll be shot?
Do you?
Yeah, do you think I'd be shot?
That's right.
If they even make it there, if they've got room for them.
And see, that's just a common belief because you know that's what happens.
You hear about justice, but America doesn't really want justice.
If they wanted justice, all they have to do is just put it in a computer.
Did you do this?
Yes?
No.
Push the button.
Guilty?
No.
or not guilty, that's the way to come out.
So if we wanted true justice, it'd be real cheap, real fast, and just push a button, and everybody would get justice.
You either did it or you didn't do it.
There's no gray.
You're not just a little bit pregnant.
You're either you are or you're not.
You've never known anybody just a little bit pregnant, have you?
Just a smidge, just kind of a little, you know, it doesn't happen, does it?
What do you think Saigon felt?
Why?
Do I think it fell?
We talked about the government being corrupt.
Well, I mean, Saigon is like the Washington.
That's their capital.
When you take over the capital, you've made a statement.
Like if the communists come in and take over New York City or Washington, D.C., they've made a statement.
They don't have to take care of Kerrville.
And it fell 15 months after we pulled out.
How did you feel when you heard that?
We were pouring out, and all those men were coming.
Well, I'll tell you what.
I'll make a statement that I told my wife.
In fact, I told her, I said, well, let me tell you what's going to happen.
They're going to come in from Cambodia, because I knew where everybody was.
And I said, they're going to go this way, and they're going to go that way.
And without exception, I called every single town, every single item, as it happened by the day.
And I did it beforehand.
You know, to my wife.
I said, this is what you hide and watch as if it don't happen.
And I mean, it happened just like I had a crystal ball.
Because as I told you before, war really is a very simple deal.
And when the opposition leaves, buddy, you just take the path of least resistance, you know.
Well, by talking to you, I can tell that you're proud of what you did because you did what you were supposed to do.
And you probably could have done it better if the politicians hadn't interfered.
Do you believe that right?
I think that's exactly right.
I'll tell you something else.
I'm not trying to beat my own tom-tom there a little bit, but I want to tell you something that I felt very strongly about.

before I went over there, and one of them is I really cared, you know, and the eight months that I was actually in the field, you know, either commanding a tank platoon or commanding some infantry type unit, you know how many Americans I got killed that was underneath my command?
Zero.
And that was in 68 and 69, the fun time, okay?
Now,

maybe a little bit of it was due to my being a tactical genius right but maybe more of it and probably a little bit more realistically I think what it really had to do with is a term that has come out of the Vietnam War is a deal called body count you know and what happens you know some real smart guy from Harvard or someplace like that makes some little statements you know like
If you can't manage it, or if you can't count it, then you can't manage it.
If you can't control what the numbers are, you don't know if you're winning or losing.
It's like cost accounting.
You kind of got to know.
So if you can't measure it, you can't manage it.
That's kind of a catchy little saying that a lot of business people use.
I think that got involved in Vietnam.

somebody said we couldn't, you know, this back, you know, they're over there, really, they were over there in 63, you know, and nobody thought too much about it, you know, then things started happening, you know, a little bit more aggressively, like in 65, and started building up, and then things got a little hotter, you know, and then everybody started asking the question, well, how do you know if you're winning, you know, so in general, ask somebody, how do we know if we're winning,
And the general says, well, we're killing more of them than they're killing us.
And we're destroying more than they're destroying.
And therefore, we're winning.
And somebody says, how do you know?
So the general says, how do we know?
Well, we don't really know for sure.
And then somebody, his advisor says, why don't we start counting?
That's a good idea.
So that's where this body count came from.
The word comes down now that we're interested in how many people you killed today.
You know, like, let's keep score.
And so you kept score.
Well, what happened then, especially with, and I'm going to say West Point people, because they are career people, and they're the ones that are in the Pentagon.
They come up with these catchy little things.
And they're the ones that basically are your career type people, not that others aren't.
And I really would have liked to have stayed in the military.
I did a good job, and I liked the Army.
But had it not been for all the politics and stuff that I saw, especially with the West Point officers and that ring knocking, you know, let you know.
They'd take their little West Point ring, and then, you know, if you start questioning this and that, they'd sit there.

knock on, it's called a ring knocker, and they're letting you know, by gosh, I'm from West Point, I know, I make the decision, you have nothing to say about anything, you know, and that's where the term ring knocker comes from, because they're all real good about doing that, you know, let you know I'm West Point.
Well, I'll tell you what, there's very few officers that have people under their command that, like I did, that can quote the kind of letters that I didn't write home, you know,
Because I saw people get people killed for no reason.
And because I really cared about your brother, your husband, your father, I wasn't going to unnecessarily risk their lives just in order to get some more body count or do this.
Now, I will also say that I accomplished every mission that I was given without exception.
Tell me to go over and do this, I did it.
But anybody killed.
That's what people wanted, but really not even real bad.
What I'd call real bad, where you're going to get real, you know.
So I was, and I'm fortunate, and I thank the Lord for that, that I didn't write those letters.
But I'll tell you what, I worked at it too.
I didn't want to write in those letters.
Because I'll tell you, if I had,
to have written a bunch of those letters.
I guarantee you I probably wouldn't, I would have had some flashbacks or how I could have done that better or that, you know, I felt real guilty or bad about that.
Well, I'm sure that your man was speaking to you and looked up more to you because they could see that you cared about them and they probably tried harder.
Did you see that?
Well, no, not necessarily.
I think everybody wasn't really concerned about that or knew one way or the other.
They were just doing their thing.
Mm-hmm.
You know, they did what they were told.
It's just that I just had, you might say, a more conservative way of going about doing things is all.
But I still got the job done.
It may have been a little slower sometimes.
You know, I may not have, you know, gone by somebody's stopwatch on me, you know.
But I got the job done properly.
If you had a message to college students today to try to clear up the misconceptions that they have about this war,
What would you say to them?
Don't believe what you read in the history books.
Because most of it was written by people who weren't there.
What would you tell them to go talk to action?
I don't know how many people they could effectively talk to.
Because you talk to me and you're getting just my version of it.
I may be the only crazy one out there, you know.
And I may be 100% wrong.
You should probably read books on people that were there that fought, such as Caputo and Raymond O'Rourke.
Did you see that?
No, I haven't read anything.
Really, to tell you the truth, I don't read anything about Lincoln.
I'll tell you the truth.
And the only reason I've seen those movies, I did want to go see the platoon because I heard so much about it, and it was written and directed by a guy who was a platoon leader.
So I felt like it would be authentic.
He did a lot of great things in there, in my opinion.
One thing that he portrayed very well in the movie was I saw fear on people's faces.
I mean, like they were just terrified, and I thought that was very real.
You know, especially in those night actions where he saw people.
Did you see it with him?
I didn't see it with him.
You ought to go see it.
You ought to go see it because
It says something, but I thought it was authentic.
I thought the decor of everything, the vegetation, the equipment, I thought it was authentic.
But I would just caution, not just Vietnam, because it's going to be like the Civil War and every other war.
No one's going to really know what we were really doing over there.
Because there's so many of the big players, the world players, like the Rockefellers, who have huge financial interests.
When I talk about Exxon, I'm talking about Rockefeller.
When I talk about Gulf, I'm talking about Rockefeller.
And they do things for business reasons.
And they get themselves in a jam, and they start hollering for our politicians to do something.
I guess.
